{"id":"astro-ph/0110056","submitter":"Denis Richard","authors":"D. Richard, F. Hersant, O. Dauchot, F. Daviaud, B. Dubrulle, J-P. Zahn","title":"A powerful local shear instability in stratified disks","comments":"submitted to Astronomy & Astrophysics, on Oct 02, 2001","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  In this paper, we show that astrophysical accretion disks are dynamically\nunstable to non-axisymmetric disturbances. This instability is present in any\nstably stratified anticyclonically sheared flow as soon as the angular velocity\ndecreases outwards. In the large Froude number limit, the maximal growth rate\nis proportional to the angular rotation velocity, and is independent of the\nstratification. In the low Froude number limit, it decreases like the inverse\nof the Froude number, thereby vanishing for unstratified, centrigugally stable\nflows. The instability is not sensitive to disk boundaries. We discuss the\npossible significance of our result, and its implications on the turbulent\nstate achieved by the disks. We conclude that this linear instability is one of\nthe best candidates for the source of turbulence in geometrically thin disks,\nand that magnetic fields can be safely ignored when studying their turbulent\nstate. The relevance of the instability for thick disks or nearly neutrally\nstratified disks remains to be explored.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 2 Oct 2001 13:52:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 8 Oct 2001 09:04:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
