{"id":"physics/0110005","submitter":"E. L. Koschmieder","authors":"E. L. Koschmieder","title":"Explanation of the mass of the muon","comments":"7 pages. See: arXiv hep-lat/0104016, hep-lat/0002016, hep-ph/0002179","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  The difference of the rest masses m(pi^+-) - m(mu^+-) is nearly equal to 1/4\nof the rest mass of the pi^(+-) mesons and is equal to the sum of the rest\nmasses of the 0.7 times 10^9 muon neutrinos (respectively anti-muon neutrinos)\nwhich are in the cubic lattice of the pi^(+-) mesons according to the standing\nwave model. In the decay of a pi^(+) or pi^(-) meson all muon neutrinos,\nrespectively anti-muon neutrinos, of the cubic lattice of the pi^(+-) mesons\nare emitted. The sum of the oscillation energies of all neutrinos in the\npi^(+-) mesons is the same as the sum of the oscillation energies of the\nremaining neutrinos in the mu^(+-) mesons. Consequently the mass of the mu^(+-)\nmesons is equal to m(pi^+-) - 0.7 times 10^9 m(nu_mu) or 0.75 times m(pi^+-),\nwithin 1% in agreement with the measured ratio m(mu^+-) / m(pi^+-) = 0.757028.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 2 Oct 2001 04:29:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
