{"id":"quant-ph/0110011","submitter":"Ke Yang","authors":"Andris Ambainis and Ke Yang","title":"Extracting Quantum Entanglement (General Entanglement Purification\n  Protocols)","comments":"30 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We study the problem of general entanglement purification protocols. Suppose\nAlice and Bob share a bipartite state $\\rho$ which is ``reasonably close'' to\nperfect EPR pairs. The only information Alice and Bob possess is a lower bound\non the fidelity of $\\rho$ and a maximally entangled state. They wish to\n``purify'' $\\rho$ using local operations and classical communication and create\na state that is arbitrarily close to EPR pairs. We prove that on average, Alice\nand Bob cannot increase the fidelity of the input state significantly. We also\nconstruct protocols that may fail with a small probability, and otherwise will\noutput states arbitrarily close to EPR pairs with very high probability. Our\nconstructions are efficient, i.e., they can be implemented by polynomial-size\nquantum circuits.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 1 Oct 2001 19:21:39 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 13 Nov 2001 21:21:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
